                        |BKB--=|CKBCoding a Room|BKB=--

   |WK0Before I start the actual document, I would first like to make a
few comments on rooms. First are the types of rooms we are looking
for here at Darkwind. We do NOT want 500 room areas where every room
is a description of one line or less. These types of rooms can be
coded by anyone and can be found on any mud. We want rooms with good,
quality descriptions where everything that is mention in the desc has
an associated, add_look, add_read, or an actual object in the room.
|RKORooms that do NOT follow this guideline will NOT be approved.

   |WK0The next point is when objects should be created. There are several
different views on this. No one is better than the other, but since I'm
writing this doc, I'm going to use the way I do it and give my reasoning
for doing it that way. Basically, you can create your objects that
are going to go in the room either before the reset function or after
it. I feel it is better to do it after mainly for one reason:
if an error occurs in the object that is being loaded and it fails
to load, the room will still load properly and function normally, but the
object causing the problem in it will not be present in the room. If
the object being created has a problem when you create your objects
before you make the room itself, it will not only not create the object,
but the room will also not be created as well. This means that you will
be creating a '0' room: A room with no descriptions, exits, etc. If
a player stumbles into one of these rooms, they will either have to quit
to get out or find a wizard to get them out. It also means that now the
room is impassable to what is beyond. Also, in creating a monster
that has the ability to move, if you create it before you create the exits
of the room it is being moved into, it will never move. If you create the
monster after the room is created, then the monster will move about normally.
 
   Now on to the creation part of the doc itself.
 
   The first part of this file is enough to make a basic room with some
interesting features. The second part details more functions that can
be called to expand your room.
|BKB------------------------------------------------------------------------
   |WK0The first lines of every room file should always be:
 
|YKB#include <mudlib.h>
#include <terrain.h>
inherit ROOM;
 
void reset(int iArg) {
  ::reset(iArg);
  if(iArg) return;
 
 Alternately, you may use:
void reset(int iArg){
  ::reset(iArg);
  if(!iArg) {

|WK0The basic difference between these versions is that the "if(iArg) return;"
statement is kinder for the game to process. If your room will have
wandering monsters, however, you can clone them in your room after
the exits are created (so they actually CAN wander) by placing the
monster creations after the "if(!iArg){ }" statement.

   With these lines in place, you are ready to add the actual properties
 of the room itself to the file. To customize your room, you call the
 following routines:
|BKB------------------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_light(n);
  |WK0This will set the light level of the room. This line needs to be in
  every room you code. 0 is dark, 1 is normal light. A number lower
  than 0 is normally a magically darkend room. And will require either
  a stronger light source or multiple light sources to illiuminate the
  room. The same is true with room with high than 1 for a light value.
  it will take more powerful darkness type magic to get a room like
  this to go dark. In 99% of most rooms you code up, 0 or 1 should be
  the light levels of the room.
 
 |BKBEXAMPLE: |YKBset_light(1);
|BKB------------------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_terrain(TER_type);
  |WK0This line sets the terrain type of the room, is this room a inside
  a structure, underground, a forest, etc. This line is also required
  in every room you code. For valid terrain types, look at the file
  |MKB'wizhelp 4.15 |WK0(terrain)' to get a listing. One room can be set with multiple
  types of terrain if necessary, for example an underwater area in the
  artic would be set as shown below. 
 
 |BKBEXAMPLE: |YKB#include <terrain.h>
              set_terrain(TER_UNDERWATER|TER_ARCTIC);
 
  |WK0This adds a terrain type after you have already set one with set_terrain.

  |WK0set_terrain(TER_UNDERGROUND);
  add_terrain(TER_RIVER);
  add_terrain(TER_INSIDE);
 
  |WK0This would be identical to initially setting the terrain of the room to:

 |YKOset_terrain(TER_UNDERGROUND|TER_RIVER|TER_INSIDE);

|WK0Use of add_terrain should be limited to when you are using a customized
room inheritable in which all the rooms already have a primary terrain
set.
|BKB------------------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_no_clean_up(1);
  |WK0This command is only needed if you have a room that you don't want the
  driver ever to clean up. By this I mean that periodically the driver
  will remove all the files that are not being used currently to reduce
  the memory and cpu usage of the mud. Some rooms NEED to be around at
  times because they are controlling other functions. You would use this
  command to ensure that the room wasn't removed from memory during the
  cleanup phase. This line is only required in the file when you don't
  want the room cleaned up. If it isn't present it defaults to cleanupable.
  For example, if you had a room used for storage, you would want it to be
  no_clean_up so that items stored in it would not be desctucted.
  Rooms which have the function "make_unique_object" are automatically
  set to no_clean_up to keep track of the unique, and do not need to 
  be set in addition to that.
|BKB------------------------------------------------------------------------

|GKBset_short("str");
  |WK0String str sets the short description of the room to str plus a
  carriage return. It automatically includes the obvious exits after the 
  description. Please capitalize the beginning of your rooms' short descs.
 
 |BKBEXAMPLE: |YKBset_short("A small demo room.");
 
|BKB------------------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_long("str");
  |WK0String str. The format ofsets the long description of the room to str.
  this line is very important and MUST be done as follows in the example.
  There are other less efficient ways to do it which will work, but they are
  not approved for use here. The last line of the long description becomes the
  obvious exits.
  The \n and the \n\ tell the compiler that the line ends there and that any
  more text needs to be started on a new line. After your description, the
  compiler will automatically add any obvious exits to the room.
 
 |BKBEXAMPLE: |YKBset_long("\
              This is the long description for a\n\
              test room here in the doc. You should\n\
              always use this format whenever you\n\
              set the long description in a room!\n");
 
  |CKOUsing the wrap() function will format your line lengths to 79 characters.

 |BKBEXAMPLE: |YKBset_long(wrap("\
This is also a room description. This room description will automatically\
be formatted to the correct size by the game."));

  |WK0You need not put a \n at the end of a wrap() statment. Any \n's that are
  placed within the wrap() will cause a line break if you need it for the effect
  (i.e., a multiple paragraph description). It should also be noted that we only
  want good, quality descriptions in all our rooms here on Darkwind. One or
  two-line descriptions in most cases are not going to be acceptable.
  When writing your long descriptions, please try to NOT put two spaces
  after each sentence. Since Darkwind is an on-line text-based service,
  we have no way to determine what font the text will be read in. So,
  since different fonts have different effects, text should only have
  one space between all characters (again, unless having a space is
  required for some visual effect). NB If you put multi-line text inside
  a wrap(), you must put a \ at the end of each line.
|BKB------------------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_night("str");
  |WK0String str.  This optional function sets an alternate long description
  of the room which will appear only at night. This allows you to have
  "the sun beats down on you," during the day and "the moon casts a
  peacful glow," during the night.  If set_night() is not used, then the
  description set by set_long is used at night as well as in the daytime.
|CKBIf using this command, your room needs to inherit SEASON_ROOM rather that inheriting ROOM.

|GKBset_dusk("str");
  |WK0String str.  As set_night(), above, but only appears during the hours
  of the setting sun.
|CKBIf using this command, your room needs to inherit SEASON_ROOM instead of inheriting ROOM.

|GKBset_dawn("str");
  |WK0String str.  As set_night(), above, but only appears during the hours
  of the rising sun.
|CKBIf using this command, your room needs to inherit SEASON_ROOM instead of inheriting ROOM.
|BKB------------------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBadd_exit("dir","/path/file");
  |WK0This will add 1 exit to the room. If you wish to have more than one
  exit, you just add an add_exit for each exit in the room. The first
  variable in the command is the exit direction, and the second variable
  is the path to the file you wish the the exit to lead to.
  There is no need to include the ".c" after the filename.
 
 |BKBEXAMPLE: |YKBadd_exit("west","/players/alarian/rooms/room2");
              add_exit("east","/players/alarian/rooms/room3");
 
|RKBDO not hardcode exits. Use the definition in your header file.
|BKB------------------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBadd_look("what","desc");
  |WK0This adds something to the room that can be looked at by the player.
  EVERY object that is mentioned in the room's description MUST have
  either an object in the room or an associated add_look to go
  along with it. If an item has both a look and a read, look shows
  both of them. Multiple items are supported the same way add_exit
  worked, with a separate add_look for each item. To do a simple one
  item looks, the following syntax is used:
 
 |BKBEXAMPLE: |YKBadd_look("picture","A fancy picture is on the wall.");
              |YKBadd_look("cricket","There is a small cricket in the corner chirping");
 
 |WK0If you wish to have one description for multiple different looks, you
 can do them as following:
 
 EXAMPLE: |YKBadd_look(({"wall","walls","floor"}),"It looks to be very smooth.");
 |BKB
  
  |CKBIf your descriptions are more than one 79 characters long, you MUST
  either wrap() them, or include \n's at the end of each line to add
  the carrage returns to the description.
|BKB------------------------------------------------------------------------
 
|GKBquery_look("what");
  |WK0If there is an add_look for "what" this will return what you would see if
  you typed "look at what". If "what" is not supplied, it will return the
  entire add_look array.
  The array is structured so that the first element is the first item you
  can look at, the second element is what you see when you look at it, the
  third element is the second thing you can look at, and the fourth is
  what you see when you look at the third element, etc.
|BKB------------------------------------------------------------------------

|GKBadd_read("what","desc");
  |WK0Adds the command/action "read" to the room for the item "what". Read
  returns the description immediately following the "what".

|CKBNOTE: This would be a good way to have a sign listed in your long desc,
and its description would be entered in this command instead of another object
for the sign. Also, an add_read can be seen by "look"ing at the "what".
 To do a simple one item looks, the following syntax is used:
 
 |BKBEXAMPLE: |YKBadd_read("menu","A normal lousy menu.\n");
              |YKBadd_read("sign","A fancy sign with swirly things on the corners!\n");
 
 |WK0If you wish more than one word to be able to call the same description,
 you can use the following format to achieve this:
 
 |BKBEXAMPLE: |YKBadd_read(({"sign","message"}),"It reads: Sell your stuff here.\n");
 
|WK0The same rules in add_look are applied to add_read.
|BKB------------------------------------------------------------------------
 
|GKBadd_trigger("trig","desc");
  |WK0Adds a command so that when the 'trig' is entered by itself at the
  prompt it returns the desc. It just writes the string desc to the
  calling player.
 
 |BKBEXAMPLE: |YKBadd_trigger("ithnar", "You say the command word and a bell gongs.\n");
 
 |YKOprompt>ithnar <----you type
 prompt>You say the command word and a bell gongs. <----room writes
 
|WK0The room writes follow the same rules are add_look and add_read descriptions.
Multiple triggers, for example:

 |BKBEXAMPLE: |YKBadd_trigger(({"sneeze","cough"}),"Yuck, don't do that!\n");

|WK0is possible, following the same rules as add_look and add_read.
 

|GKBremove_trigger("trig");
  |WK0Removes a trigger that has been added with add_trigger. The argument to
  remove_trigger must be a string exactly matching the 1st argument
  given to the add_trigger you wish to remove.

|BKB------------------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBmake_object("name","file_path", howmany);
  |WK0Clones and moves objects or monsters into the room. Name is the name
  of the object. You must name the object here what it is called in
  the object itself. If you do not do this, it will not find the object
  each time it checks for it and will then clone a new one. File_path is
  the pathname of the object you want to put in the room. Howmany is
  the number of objects that you want in the room, if howmany isn't
  set the default is one.
 
 |BKBEXAMPLE: |YKBmake_object("orc","/players/alarian/monsters/orc",3);

|RKBDO not hardcode items. Use the definition in your header file.

  |WK0This will put three orc from the file players/alarian/monsters/orc
  into the room. It should also be noted that if this function is called
  from inside the reset function, it will only be called with the
  room is first created. If you want the object to be recloned each
  reset, you need to put the make_object function outside the reset.
  This means, either place it BEFORE the:

 |WK0if(iArg) return; |WK0statement
or either before or after the:

 |WK0if(!iArg)|WK0{ ...stuff... } statement.

This command will clone "howmany" objects into the room, provided
there are _NO_ objects with the same ID as the "name" in the function.
If you want the room to clone enough objects each reset, regardless
of how many are left over from the previous reset, to equal "howmany",
use the add_clone function explained later in this doc.
|BKB------------------------------------------------------------------------
 
|GKBmake_unique_object("id","file_path");
 |WK0This function is almost identical to make_object, except it will allow
 only one of the object in the game at a time. This is used for powerful
 items, wandering monsters, or just items that you don't want a lot of 
 in the game.
 
|BKBEXAMPLE:  |YKBmake_unique_object("widowmaker","/players/alarian/weapons/widowmaker");
|RKBDO not hardcode items. Use the definition in your header file.

|BKB------------------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBmake_room_unique("id","file_path");|WK0
 |WK0This function is almost identical to make_unique_object, except
 it is only to be used for wandering mobs. The information is
 saved in the room, and does not use the unique daemon.

|BKB------------------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBadd_clone("file_path", num);
 |WK0Once again, this is very similar to make_object except for one main
 difference. With add_clone, if you have it creating 3 objects and
 when reset comes around and only one is currenty in the room, it will
 create to more to bring the total back upto three.
 
 |BKBEXAMPLE: |YKBadd_clone("/players/alarian/monsters/orc",3);
|RKBDO not hardcode items. Use the definition in your header file.

 |WK0This will create three orcs in the room and maintain it at that amount
 each reset.
 
|BKB--------------------------------------------------------------------------
|BKB--------------------------------------------------------------------------
|BKB--------------------------------------------------------------------------
|BKB--------------------------------------------------------------------------

|WK0Here ends the basic section of the doc. The functions above are enough to
make a decent room with things to look at and monsters and items to find.
Next comes some more esoteric functions that can add spice and enjoyment
to the rooms.
 
|GKBstatus dir_hook() {what to do}
  |WK0Takes direction "dir" and calls this function anytime somebody tries
  to use that direction. dir is any of the exits defined in add_exit().
  If the function returns 1, the exit fails and the player can't go that way.
  A return value of 0 allows the player to pass.
 
|BKBEXAMPLE:
 |YKBstatus west_hook() {
 if(present("my_unique_orc",this_object())){
 write("The orc blocks you from going that way.\n");
 say(this_player()->query_name()+" tried to go west.\n");
 return 1; /* the player can't go through */
 }
 return 0; /* the player can go through */
 }

|WK0This is a good way to keep wandering NPC's within your own area, or
in a certain range within your area.

|BKBEXAMPLE: 
 |YKBstatus out_hook(){
   return this_player()->query_npc();
 }

|WK0Remember, you pretty much never want to block wizards using dir_hooks.
The appropriate check to make sure you do not block wizards is to
#include <perms.h> at the head of your room, and put the check:

 |YKOif(IS_APPLICANT(this_player())) return 0;

|WK0at the beginning of your dir_hook().
 
 It should also be noted that this function is placed OUTSIDE the
 room creation function entirely. It is its own function. See the
 example that follows for more details.
|BKB--------------------------------------------------------------------------

|GKBset_exit_blocker(sDirection, sName, sFile, sMess);
  |WK0This is a simpler version of the dir_hooks when you have
  a simple hook. It will check for a sName that matches sFile,
  and give sMess+"\n" if the player can't go that way. This
  allows you to make sure that the sName present in the room
  is the actual file you wish to block sDirection, and not
  any stray object. sMess has a default message if not set
  of "Something blocks you from going that way."
  It also innately has the IS_APPLICANT check, so you don't
  need a seperate check. Unlike dir_hooks, this is in the
  room code.
  If you want more than one object to block the same direction,
  you will need to use a regular dir_hook. If you need more
  checks or versatility, again you'll need to use a regular
  dir_hook.
|BKB  Example:
    |YKBset_exit_blocker("north","orc",MYNPC+"orc","You no get by me!");

|BKB--------------------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_property(sAttribute,sXarg);
 |WK0This funtion sets attributes within rooms.  Attributes currently
 used are : 
 no_dirs - hides the visible exits from the players
 no_castle - deprecated, we no longer drop wizard castles
 no_teleport - don't allow teleportation skills
 no_kill - don't allow any combat
 no_wimpy - dont allow any livings to wimpy from the room
 no_tell - don't allow tells to be sent from the room
 no_shout - don't allow shouts to be sent from the room
 open_pk - combat in the room ignores PK restrictions
 no_mining - don't allow 'mine ore'
 no_herbalism - don't allow 'gather herbs'
 sXarg will be returned when query_property is called using sAttribute. 
 (see below)
 squeeze_block - "direction" - Block Morpher Squeeze in a single direction
               - "all" - Block Morpher Squeeze in ALL directions
               - "monster_id" - Block Morpher Squeeze if monster_id is present

|GKBquery_property(sAttribute);
 |WK0With an arg it returns the property given as arg. Without an arg,
 it returns all the properties defines by the following functions.
 For example, set_property("no_tell","cave"), will return "cave"
 when query_property("no_tell") is called in the environment()
 of the player.  This is used to block tells from certain rooms
 today.  The tell function looks for the "no_tell" property, just
 as shout looks for "no_shout".
 
|BKB--------------------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_no_show_exit();
  |WK0Prevents the exits from a room from being included in the long desc.
  It sets the no_dirs property.
 
 |BKBEXAMPLE: |YKBset_no_show_exit();
 
|GKBset_no_dirs();
  |WK0This is the same as setno_show_exit();
|BKB--------------------------------------------------------------------------

|GKBset_no_kill();
  |WK0Sets the property no_kill. Rooms with this property will not allow combat.
 
 |BKBEXAMPLE: |YKBset_no_kill();
|BKB--------------------------------------------------------------------------

|GKBset_no_teleport();
  |WK0Sets the no_teleport flag for querying from outside objects. This
  adds the no_teleport property. Set this is you have a room that you 
  don't want players to be able to teleport into or out of.
 
|BKBEXAMPLE: |YKBset_no_teleport();
|BKB--------------------------------------------------------------------------

|GKBset_no_short();
  |WK0This command will make the 'exits' or 'autoexit' return the short
  of "Unknown" instead of the rooms actual short description. This
  can be used in rooms where you don't want players to know whats
  in a given room until they have actually entered it.

|GKBquery_no_short();
  |WK0Returns 1 if set_no_short(); has been set, 0 if not. Currently
  only used by the 'exits' and 'autoexits' function.

|BKB--------------------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBset_room_open_pk(status tVal);
  |WK0This command will make the room open_pk if tVal is 1, or return
  the room to normal if tVal is 0. Combat will be allowed as if
  everyone was PK. All normal checks apply, like no_kill, etc.

|GKBquery_room_open_pk();
  |WK0Returns 1 if set_room_open_pk(1), 0 otherwise.

|BKB--------------------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBremove_exit("str");
  |WK0Lets you remove an exit from a room depending on circumstances.
 
 |BKBEXAMPLE: |YKBremove_exit("west");
 
 
|GKBremove_look("str");
  |WK0Same usage as remove_trigger and remove_exit.

|BKB--------------------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBquery_exit("str");
  |WK0Str is the exit direction, west, north, etc. With an arg, it returns
  the file that the exit goes to. Without and arg it returns the whole
  list of exits defined by add_exit().
 
 |BKBEXAMPLE: |YKBquery_exit("west");
 |WK0or
 |WKBquery_exit();
 
|BKB--------------------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBquery_triggers(str);
  |WK0Str is the trigger command, ie. foof. With an arg it returns the string
  that the trigger returns. Without an arg it returns the whole list of
  triggers defined by add_trigger();
  The str can be a variable <sFoof> that ids to a string or it can be the
  string <"foof"> itself.
 
 |BKBEXAMPLE: |YKBquery_triggers(sFoof);
          query_triggers("foof");
 |WK0or
 |YKBquery_triggers();
 
|BKB--------------------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBquery_no_kill();
  |WK0Returns the value of no_kill;
 
 |BKBEXAMPLE: |YKBquery_no_kill();
 
|BKB--------------------------------------------------------------------------
|GKBquery_no_teleport();
  |WK0Returns the value of no_teleport;
 
 |BKBEXAMPLE: |YKBquery_no_teleport();
|BKB--------------------------------------------------------------------------

  |WK0The following functions are for use in setting room chats that are
  sent like echos to a room. They are nice for adding flavor text to the
  rooms without having to create invisible mobs doing the chatting. The
  chats only run when there are players in the room.

|GKBset_chat_chance(n);
  |WK0This will set the chance of the chat being spammed. If random(100)
  is less than n, the message is skipped that time.

|GKBset_chat_delay(int iDelay, int iRandomDelay);
  |WK0This will set the delay between when messages will be spammed
  to the room. The delay will be iDelay + random(iRandomDelay). The
  default is 2 seconds if no delay is set, so please set one.
 
 |BKBEXAMPLE: |YKBset_chat_delay(20,30);

|GKBadd_room_chat(string sMsg);
  |WK0This will add a message that will be told to the room. You must
  include the "\n" at the end of the string. You would have to use
  add_room_chat multiple times to add more than one message, and the
  messages are a random from the total chats added.

  |BKBEXAMPLE:  |YKBadd_room_chat("The floorboards creak underfoot.\n");

|GKBremove_room_chat(string sMsg);
  |WK0This will remove sMsg from the possible strings being sent to
  the room. It must match exactly to the string added with
  add_room_chat.

|GKBset_room_chat_check(string sFunc);
  |WK0Allows you to set a function the room will check before spamming
  the message to the room. If the function returns 0, no message will
  spam, and all the room chats will stop. The chats will resume if
  someone enters the room, and the function returns 1.

|BKB------------------------------------------------------------------------
|WK0If you plan on having a door in your room, you need to be first familiar
with this file and how to create rooms, then you need to read through the
doc 'wizhelp 4.8 (doors)' and it will go through the step by step process for
adding a door to your room.
 
Also, if you are going to be adding additional functions to a room that
you wish to define yourself, you need to enable the commands in the
following manner. NOTE: This all goes after all the room creation code
is completely finished.
 
|YKOvoid init() {
 ::init();
 add_action("yourfunction","name_of_function");
 add_action("your2ndfunction","name_of_2nd_function");
 etc
}
 
|WK0More on adding your own functions can be found elsewhere. (or ask an ARCH+
for assistance).
|BKB--------------------------------------------------------------------------
|BKB---------------------------------------------------------------------------
|WK0Following now is an example that uses most of the more commonly used
functions of ROOM.
 

|CKB#include <mudlib.h>
#include <terrain.h>
#include <perms.h>
inherit ROOM;
 
void reset(int iArg) {
  ::reset(iArg);
  make_unique_object("greatsword","/players/alarian/weapons/hellspawn");
  add_clone("/players/alarian/monsters/demon",6);
  if(iArg) return;
  set_light(0); /* Light level of room (dark here) */
  set_terrain(TER_UNDERGROUND|TER_ARCTIC); /* An underground room in
                                                   the tundra. */
  set_short("A frozen cavern"); /* what is seen by players in
                                          brief mode. */
  set_long("\
This room is deep underground. There are pools of frozen water\n\
scattered about in most of the depressions in the floor,\n\
and strange writings can be seen on the west wall. There\n\
is a small opening leading out of the cavern to the west.\n");
  add_exit("west","/players/alarian/rooms/cave2");
  add_look(({"pool","pools"}),"A thin film of ice covers cold pools of water.");
  add_look(({"depression","depressions"}),"A low spot in the floor.");
  add_look("walls","They are stone walls. There is writing on the west wall.");
  add_look( ({"wall","west wall","western wall"}), "\
There is a small opening in the western wall, and some writing you\n\
could read.");
  add_read("writings","\
It seems to be written in a strange tongue and\n\
you can't decipher what is says. Although if you\n\
had to make a guess, you would say that whatever\n\
is written is written in elvish.\n");
  set_no_teleport();
}

status west_hook() {
  if(IS_APPLICANT(this_player())) return 0;
  if(present("demon",this_object())) {
    write("The demon prevents you from leaving!\n");
    say(this_player()->query_name()+" was blocked by the demons!\n");
    return 1; /* the player can't go through */
  }
  return 0; /* the player can go through */
}
 
|RKBDO not hardcode items. Use the definition in your header file.

|WK0The above example created a room with a good description, that has add_looks
or add_reads for everything in the description. It also has a unique object
and several demons that prevents anyone from leaving once they have entered
the room until all the demons are killed.
 
Good luck, if you find any problems or confusing sections in this
article use typo/idea/bug to report them. If you have any questions
as another BUILDER+, use the Builder line, or post on the Main
Wiz board.

